"""
mkt-original fill — 1 Samuel ch25-27
Covers: 72 missing verses (ch25: 40 missing; ch26: 22 missing; ch27: 10 missing)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-1samuel-25-27-fill.py

Key decisions:
- ch25 v25: nāḇāl šᵉmô ûnᵉḇālāh ʿimmô — explicit name-play between Nabal and nᵉḇālāh
- ch25 v29: ṣᵉrûrāh — "bundle/pouch" of the living; rare term rendered "bound up" in MKT
- ch25 v37: lēḇ nabal mēt — "his heart died within him"; medical event, not metaphor
- ch26 v12: tardēmāh — primordial deep sleep (same word as Gen 2:21, Jonah 1:5)
- ch26 v19: if human instigation, curse is that David is driven to ʿăḇōḏ ʾelōhîm ʾăḥērîm
- ch27 v6: Ziklag etiological note — belongs to kings of Judah "to this day"
"""

import json
import pathlib

def load_comm(path):
    p = pathlib.Path(path)
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(path, data):
    pathlib.Path(path).write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new commentary entries without overwriting existing ones — safe to re-run
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
"25": {
"1": "<p>Samuel&#8217;s death notice interrupts the Saul-David pursuit narrative: <em>wayyāmot šᵉmûʾēl</em> — Samuel died; all Israel gathered and mourned (<em>wayyispadû</em>) and buried him at his home in Ramah. The terse report marks the passing of the last figure who could mediate between Saul and YHWH. Samuel&#8217;s burial at Ramah closes the narrative arc that opened there (1 Sam 1:1; 7:17); his death removes the prophetic voice that had anointed both kings. David&#8217;s subsequent movement to the wilderness of Paran repositions the narrative geographically — Paran (southern wilderness, associated with Ishmael and the Mosaic wilderness wanderings) frames the Nabal episode in a landscape of testing.</p>",

"2": "<p>Nabal&#8217;s introduction: a man in Maon (<em>ʾîš bᵉMāʿôn</em>) with property in Carmel, very great (<em>wᵉhāʾîš gāḏôl mᵉʾōḏ</em>) in wealth — three thousand sheep and a thousand goats. The combination of Maon and Carmel locates him in the hill country southwest of Hebron, David&#8217;s tribal heartland. The wealth enumerated — flocks measured in thousands — establishes him as a major pastoral landowner in exactly the territory David&#8217;s men have been protecting. The narrative sets up the economic relationship before introducing the characters: the wealth exists; the question is whether it will be shared.</p>",

"3": "<p>The character introduction of Nabal and Abigail in a single verse establishes the narrative&#8217;s moral axis before the action begins. Nabal&#8217;s name (<em>nāḇāl</em>) means fool — a name the narrative will treat as character destiny. Abigail&#8217;s name (<em>ʾăḇîgayil</em>, possibly &#8220;father&#8217;s joy&#8221;) signals her positive role. The contrasting characterizations are explicit: <em>ṭôḇat seḵel wîpat toʾar</em> (good of understanding and beautiful of form) for Abigail; <em>qāšeh wᵉraʿ maʿălālîm</em> (harsh and evil in his deeds) for Nabal. His Calebite lineage is noted without explanation — perhaps ironically, since Caleb was a man of faithful loyalty to YHWH (Num 14:24).</p>",

"4": "<p>David hears in the wilderness that Nabal is shearing his sheep — the festival occasion that triggered the request. Shearing time was a period of celebration and generosity in pastoral culture (cf. 2 Sam 13:23-24 where Absalom uses shearing time for a feast); requests for provisions at such times were socially legitimate and expected. David&#8217;s information network — he &#8220;hears&#8221; even in the wilderness — reflects both his intelligence-gathering capacity and his integration into Judean social networks. The timing of the request at shearing is not opportunistic but customary.</p>",

"5": "<p>David sends ten young men (<em>ʿăśārāh nᵉʿārîm</em>) with instructions to greet Nabal in his name (<em>bišmî</em>). The formal delegation signals that this is an official request by the leader of a significant force, not a private appeal. The instruction to greet him with the threefold peace — <em>šālôm ʾăḥîḵā</em> (peace to your brother), followed by extended greetings — employs standard ancient Near Eastern epistolary formulas of diplomatic approach before a petition.</p>",

"6": "<p>The opening greeting formula — <em>lɛḥay</em> (to life! — a toast/blessing), followed by the threefold <em>šālôm</em> to Nabal, his household, and all that is his — is the most elaborate greeting formula in the Hebrew Bible. The word <em>lɛḥay</em> is unusual as an address particle; the LXX reads <em>eis etos</em> (for a year/long life). The repetition of <em>šālôm</em> (three times) over the person, household, and possessions marks the greeting as a comprehensive blessing — David&#8217;s men come in peace and wish to be received in peace.</p>",

"7": "<p>David&#8217;s claim of protective service: <em>lōʾ hᵉḵalmûnûm</em> (we did not insult/shame them) and <em>lōʾ nippāqēḏ lāhem mᵉʾûmāh</em> (nothing was missing to them all the days they were in Carmel). The verb <em>kālam</em> (to insult, shame) and the term <em>nippāqēḏ</em> (was missing, from <em>pāqaḏ</em> — to number/inspect) establish the specific claims: no social dishonor, no material loss. This is the vocabulary of covenant loyalty — David is claiming he acted as a faithful protective ally, not merely a passive neighbor.</p>",

"8": "<p>The petition itself: <em>māṣᵉʾû nāʾ haNNᵉʿārîm ḥēn bᵉʿêneḵā</em> — let the young men find favor in your eyes. The word <em>ḥēn</em> (favor, grace) frames the request as an appeal to generosity rather than a demand for payment. The phrase <em>yôm ṭôḇ</em> (a good day, a festive day) locates the appeal within the cultural framework of shearing celebration, when generosity was both expected and ritually appropriate. The closing formula — &#8220;give to your servants and to your son David&#8221; — is a formal petition structure subordinating David&#8217;s identity to the social relationship.</p>",

"9": "<p>The young men deliver David&#8217;s message, wait (<em>wayyānûḥû</em>), and await Nabal&#8217;s response. The waiting creates narrative pause before Nabal&#8217;s shocking reply. The verb <em>nûaḥ</em> (to rest, settle) subtly contrasts with Nabal&#8217;s restless hostility about to erupt — the messengers rest in expectation of hospitality; Nabal will disturb that rest with refusal.</p>",

"10": "<p>Nabal&#8217;s response is a cascade of contemptuous rhetorical questions: <em>mî dāwîḏ ûmî ben yišay</em> — Who is David and who is the son of Jesse? The repetition of &#8220;who is&#8221; twice dismisses David&#8217;s identity and lineage simultaneously. The phrase <em>hārabbû hayōm haʿăḇāḏîm hammitp̄arᵉṣîm</em> (many servants today are breaking away from their masters) casts David as a runaway slave rather than a loyal chieftain — a direct inversion of David&#8217;s self-presentation. The contempt is also a political statement: Nabal aligns himself with Saul&#8217;s view of David as a rebel.</p>",

"11": "<p>Nabal&#8217;s refusal uses a series of possessive pronouns that reveal his theology: <em>laḥmî ûmêmay ûṭiḇḥātî</em> — my bread, my water, my slaughtered meat. Everything is possessive; there is no social horizon beyond ownership. The rhetorical question — why should I give to men I do not know where they are from? — inverts the hospitality ethic. In the ancient Near East, not-knowing did not relieve the host obligation; Nabal uses it as an excuse. His &#8220;not knowing&#8221; (<em>lōʾ yāḏaʿtî</em>) ironically echoes the fool&#8217;s characteristic cognitive failure in Proverbs.</p>",

"12": "<p>The young men return and report everything (<em>wayyaggᵉḏû lô kᵉḵōl haddᵉḇārîm</em>). The full reporting ensures David has complete information before acting. The narrative&#8217;s economy — the complete report in a single phrase — moves quickly to David&#8217;s reaction, which will be immediate and disproportionate, requiring Abigail&#8217;s intervention.</p>",

"13": "<p>David&#8217;s response: <em>ḥigru ʾîš ʾet ḥarbô</em> — every man strap on his sword. The triple repetition of the command and its compliance — David straps on, the men strap on — emphasizes the military mobilization. Four hundred go up with David; two hundred remain with the supplies. The force represents two-thirds of his fighting capacity deployed for what amounts to personal revenge — a serious miscalculation that Abigail&#8217;s intervention will prevent. The term <em>hak kᵉlîm</em> (supplies/equipment) for the remaining two hundred anticipates the distribution formula of ch30:24.</p>",

"14": "<p>One of Nabal&#8217;s servants (<em>ʾeḥāḏ minnᵉʿārîm</em>) goes to Abigail with intelligence. The servant&#8217;s report to Abigail rather than to Nabal signals his assessment of the household dynamics — Nabal cannot be reasoned with; Abigail is the competent party. The servant&#8217;s description of David&#8217;s messengers — &#8220;our lord railed at them&#8221; (<em>wayyaʿēṭ ʾălêhem</em>) — uses a verb meaning to fly at/pounce on, conveying Nabal&#8217;s aggressive verbal assault on the diplomatic party.</p>",

"15": "<p>The servant&#8217;s testimony to David&#8217;s protective service: <em>ṭôḇîm hāʾănāšîm mᵉʾōḏ lānû</em> — the men were very good to us. The servant confirms from firsthand experience what David had claimed: no insult (<em>lōʾ hōḵalmūnû</em>), nothing missing (<em>lōʾ pāqadnû mᵉʾûmāh</em>), the entire time in the field. The servant&#8217;s testimony is an independent corroboration of the justice of David&#8217;s claim, raising the moral stakes of Nabal&#8217;s refusal.</p>",

"16": "<p>The servant&#8217;s climactic image: <em>ḥômāh hāyû ʿālênû gam laylāh gam yômām</em> — they were a wall to us, both by night and by day, all the days we were with them keeping the sheep. The metaphor of a wall (<em>ḥômāh</em>) for David&#8217;s protection is military and architectural — a complete surrounding defense. The temporal comprehensiveness — both night and day — underscores the constant nature of the protection. This is the vocabulary of fortress defense applied to shepherds in the field, making David&#8217;s claim of service concrete and vivid.</p>",

"17": "<p>The servant&#8217;s warning: &#8220;know and see what you are going to do, because harm is determined against our master and against all his household.&#8221; The verb <em>kālᵉtāh</em> (determined/finished) from <em>kālāh</em> expresses finality — the danger is not hypothetical but settled. The servant&#8217;s description of Nabal as <em>ben bᵉliyyaʿal</em> (son of Belial/worthlessness) — the same phrase Abigail will use — shows that his own household recognized his character. The servant cannot approach Nabal because Nabal is one &#8220;from whom one cannot speak to.&#8221;</p>",

"18": "<p>Abigail&#8217;s response is immediate and comprehensive: she takes <em>mahayrāh</em> (quickly/with haste) — the same word used of emergency in war narratives. The list of provisions she assembles is precise: 200 loaves of bread, 2 skins of wine, 5 dressed sheep (<em>ḥămēš ṣōʾn ʿăśûyôt</em>), 5 seahs of roasted grain (<em>qālit</em>), 100 clusters of raisins (<em>ṣimmûqîm</em>), 200 pressed fig cakes (<em>dᵉḇēlîm</em>). The enumeration signals administrative competence — Abigail knows exactly what she has and deploys it precisely. The provisions mirror David&#8217;s men&#8217;s numbers (approximately) and quality, demonstrating serious hospitality.</p>",

"19": "<p>Abigail sends the provisions ahead and follows on her donkey, telling her servants to go on ahead; she says nothing to Nabal (<em>lᵉʾîšāh nāḇāl lōʾ higgîḏāh</em>). The explicit note that she conceals her action from Nabal is both practical — he would have sabotaged it — and theologically significant. She acts independently of her household head in order to save the household. The concealment from the fool to protect his household from his own folly anticipates wisdom-literature themes: the wise woman builds her household (Prov 14:1) while the foolish man tears it down.</p>",

"20": "<p>The encounter on the mountain: Abigail descends by the covert/shelter of the mountain (<em>bᵉsēter hāhār</em>) and meets David and his men coming up. The topographic detail places the meeting in a sheltered ravine or overhang — a space that mirrors the concealment motif. <em>Sēter</em> (shelter, hiddenness) is frequently used theologically of divine protection (Ps 27:5; 91:1); here the geographical shelter becomes the space of providential meeting. David had already vowed destruction; the encounter at the sēter is the pivot point of the narrative.</p>",

"21": "<p>The narrator provides access to David&#8217;s internal speech: <em>wayyōʾmer dāwid ʾaḵ lašśāwᵉʾ šāmartî</em> — David had been saying, &#8220;Indeed it was for nothing I guarded all this man&#8217;s possessions in the wilderness.&#8221; The particle <em>ʾaḵ</em> (surely, indeed) marks bitter irony — all the protective service has produced nothing. <em>Šāwᵉʾ</em> (emptiness/vanity) is the vocabulary of futility found in Ecclesiastes. David&#8217;s complaint is theologically resonant: he perceives his faithfulness as unrewarded, which is precisely when the temptation to take matters into his own hands is strongest.</p>",

"22": "<p>David&#8217;s oath of destruction: <em>kōh yaʿăśeh ʾelōhîm lᵉʾōyᵉḇê ḏāwîḏ wᵉḵōh yōsîp</em> — the self-imprecation formula. The target of his oath: <em>ʾim ʾašʾîr min-kol ʾăšer lô ʿad habbōqer min-hammazkîr ʿal qîr</em> — if I leave of all that belongs to him until morning so much as one male. The phrase <em>hammazkîr ʿal qîr</em> (one who urinates on a wall) is a contemptuous idiom for males. David&#8217;s intention is complete destruction of Nabal&#8217;s male line — a disproportionate response that the narrator presents without endorsement, setting up Abigail&#8217;s intervention as the correction of David&#8217;s error.</p>",

"23": "<p>Abigail&#8217;s full prostration: <em>wayyihî kirʾôt ʾăḇîgayil ʾet dāwid wattᵉmaher wattēred mēʿal haḥămôr wattippōl lᵉpānê dāwid ʿal pānēyhā wattišataḥû ʾāreṣ</em> — she fell before David on her face and bowed to the ground. The multiple verbs of rapid action (hurried, descended, fell) convey urgent, total submission. The prostration is simultaneously diplomatic (submission to power) and intercessory (pleading on behalf of the guilty) — Abigail takes on herself the posture of one who acknowledges wrongdoing even though she herself is innocent.</p>",

"24": "<p><em>ʾăḏōnî tᵉhî nāʾ hāʿăwōn bî</em> — let the guilt rest on me, my lord. Abigail&#8217;s opening is a vicarious guilt-assumption formula — she places herself as mediator by absorbing the liability. This is not merely diplomatic flattery but a structured intercession: by taking the guilt upon herself, she creates space for David to act mercifully without loss of honor. The speech that follows is one of the longest and most sophisticated in the Samuel narrative, combining legal argument, theological reflection, and prophetic foresight.</p>",

"26": "<p>Abigail invokes YHWH and David&#8217;s own life as witnesses: <em>waʿattāh ʾăḏōnî ḥay YHWH wᵉḥê napšᵉḵā</em>. The dual oath-formula is the highest form of appeal — both the divine name and the personal oath of the one addressed. She then articulates a theology of divine restraint: YHWH has kept David from coming into bloodguilt (<em>mibôʾ bᵉdāmîm</em>) and from taking vengeance into his own hand (<em>hôšîaʿ yāḏᵉḵā lāḵ</em>). The interpretation frames the providential meeting itself as YHWH&#8217;s intervention — David&#8217;s restraint is not weakness but divine gift.</p>",

"27": "<p>The gift (<em>habbᵉrāḵāh</em> — blessing) is what Abigail has brought. The term <em>bᵉrāḵāh</em> (blessing) for the provision reframes the transaction: this is not simply provisions but a covenantal blessing, the concrete embodiment of the goodwill between David&#8217;s camp and Nabal&#8217;s household. The request that it be given to the young men who follow David — <em>lannᵉʿārîm hammiṯhallᵉḵîm bᵉraglê ʾăḏōnî</em> (who walk at the feet of my lord) — uses the idiom of faithful following that implies covenant loyalty.</p>",

"30": "<p>Abigail&#8217;s prophetic foresight: <em>wᵉhāyāh kî yaʿăśeh YHWH laʾăḏōnî ʾet kol ʾăšer dibber haṭṭôḇ</em> — when YHWH has done for my lord all the good he has spoken. The phrase acknowledges that YHWH has made specific promises to David (<em>dibber haṭṭôḇ</em> — spoken the good) — she knows about the prophetic promises of kingship. Her speech demonstrates that David&#8217;s destiny as king is known in Judean circles even before his enthronement. She projects forward to the time David will be appointed ruler (<em>nāgîḏ</em>) over Israel.</p>",

"31": "<p><em>wᵉlōʾ tihyeh zōʾt lᵉḵā lᵉpûḵāh ûlᵉmiḵšôl lēḇ</em> — this will not be a stumbling block or obstacle of heart for you. The terms <em>pûḵāh</em> (stumbling/wavering) and <em>miḵšôl</em> (stumbling block) describe the psychological and spiritual burden of unnecessary bloodguilt on a future king. Abigail argues not just ethically but consequentially: king David cannot afford to have blood vengeance in his history. She requests that when YHWH prospers David, he remember her (<em>wᵉzāḵartā ʾet ʾămaṯᵉḵā</em>) — a modest request that frames her entire intervention as an act of faith-filled service.</p>",

"33": "<p>David blesses Abigail&#8217;s <em>ṭaʿam</em> (discernment/good judgment — literally &#8220;taste,&#8221; extended to wisdom) and herself: <em>bārûḵ ṭaʿmēḵ ûḇᵉrûḵāh ʾātt</em>. The blessing of her judgment before blessing her person emphasizes that wisdom is the quality being honored. The reason: <em>ʾăšer kᵉlîtinî hayyôm hazzeh mibôʾ bᵉdāmîm</em> — she kept David from coming into bloodguilt. David explicitly acknowledges that he was on the verge of serious sin and that her intervention was salvific. This is a rare moment of Davidic self-awareness and gratitude for external correction.</p>",

"34": "<p>David&#8217;s oath: as YHWH God of Israel lives, who held me back from harming her — if she had not hurried to meet him, there would not have been left to Nabal by the morning light <em>ʿad habbōqer məʾîr</em> so much as a male. The completion of the interrupted oath from v22 creates a rhetorical frame — David now completes his violent oath as a counterfactual, acknowledging that the oath&#8217;s execution was wrong and that Abigail&#8217;s intervention was the only thing that prevented it. The theological point: YHWH restrained David through a human instrument.</p>",

"35": "<p>David accepts the provisions and sends Abigail home in peace: <em>ʿălî lᵉšālôm lᵉḇêtēḵ</em>. The three words parallel the threefold <em>šālôm</em> of the original greeting (v6), completing a verbal circle — the peace David&#8217;s men wished on Nabal&#8217;s household is now granted by David to its representative. He has accepted both her intercession (<em>šāmaʿtî bᵉqōlēḵ</em> — I have heeded your voice) and her person (<em>wāʾeśśāʾ pānāyiḵ</em> — I have honored your face).</p>",

"36": "<p>Nabal&#8217;s feast: <em>miššᵉtēh hammelek</em> — a feast like a king&#8217;s. The irony is pointed: Nabal is feasting royally while the actual future king was approaching with drawn swords. <em>Lēḇ Nabal ṭôḇ ʿālāyw</em> — Nabal&#8217;s heart was good (glad) upon him, <em>wᵉhû šiḵḵōr ʿad mᵉʾōḏ</em> — and he was very drunk. Abigail says nothing to him until morning — <em>ʿad ʾôr habbōqer</em> — respecting both his incapacity and the gravity of what she must tell him. The scene of oblivious feasting while danger has passed mirrors ironic moments in the wisdom tradition.</p>",

"37": "<p>The morning revelation and Nabal&#8217;s collapse: when Abigail tells him everything, <em>wayyāmot libbô bᵉqirbô wᵉhû hāyāh lᵉʾāḇen</em> — his heart died within him and he became like a stone. The two stages — heart-death, then petrification — describe a serious cardiac event (perhaps a stroke followed by catatonia). The language <em>lᵉʾāḇen</em> (to stone/rock) is unique here; the petrification of the one who refused the living rock of hospitality is deeply ironic. Nabal&#8217;s name meant fool, and his heart-death is the fool&#8217;s ultimate destiny (cf. Ps 14:1; 53:1 — the fool says in his heart).</p>",

"38": "<p>Ten days later YHWH strikes Nabal (<em>wayyiggōp YHWH ʾet nāḇāl wayyāmot</em>) and he dies. The ten-day interval between Nabal&#8217;s stroke and his death creates narrative distance — David does not kill Nabal, and YHWH&#8217;s agency is unambiguous. The verb <em>nāgap</em> (to strike, plague) is used of divine plague-sending (Exod 12:23; 1 Sam 6:9); its use here marks Nabal&#8217;s death as covenantal judgment rather than natural illness. The narrative carefully exonerates David from Nabal&#8217;s blood while attributing judgment to YHWH.</p>",

"39": "<p>David&#8217;s response to Nabal&#8217;s death: <em>bārûḵ YHWH ʾăšer rāḇ ʾet rîḇ ḥerpātî</em> — blessed be YHWH who has pleaded (<em>rāḇ</em>) the cause of my shame/insult. The verb <em>rîḇ</em> (to plead/contend) places YHWH in the role of legal advocate — YHWH has been David&#8217;s attorney in the dispute with Nabal. The phrase <em>wᵉʾet ʿaḇdô ḥāśaḵ mērāʿāh</em> — and has withheld his servant from evil — acknowledges retrospectively that David was about to do wrong. The marriage request to Abigail follows immediately, framed as recognition of her wisdom and faithfulness.</p>",

"40": "<p>David sends his servants to Abigail at Carmel to propose marriage. The formal sending of servants (<em>šālaḥ dāwid waydabbēr bᵉʾăḇîgayil lᵉqaḥtāh lô lᵉʾiššāh</em>) is the proper marriage-proposal protocol — a king does not go himself but sends representatives. The marriage proposal arrives as Nabal&#8217;s body is barely cold (implied sequence); the narrative&#8217;s speed here is notable, reinforcing that David recognized in Abigail not merely a rescuer but a potential political and personal partner.</p>",

"41": "<p>Abigail&#8217;s acceptance speech: <em>hinnēh ʾămaṭᵉḵā lᵉšiphāh liRḥōṣ raglay ʾaḏōnî</em> — behold your servant as a maidservant to wash the feet of my lord&#8217;s servants. The formula of self-abasement — offering to wash the feet of the servants of her husband-to-be — inverts the expected social hierarchy; she was a wealthy landowner&#8217;s wife. The foot-washing image (<em>raḥaṣ raglaym</em>) carries the weight of total servitude. Her acceptance mirrors her earlier prostration; Abigail consistently presents herself as the servant even when the narrative has shown her as the wise leader.</p>",

"42": "<p>Abigail&#8217;s departure: <em>waqqām ʾăḇîgayil mahayrāh</em> — Abigail rose quickly. The adverb <em>mahayrāh</em> mirrors v18&#8217;s <em>wattᵉmaher</em> — the same urgency that characterized her intervention now marks her response to the marriage offer. She takes five maidens (<em>ḥāmēš nᵉʿārôteyhā</em>) and follows David&#8217;s messengers, becoming his wife. The five maidens are a token of her former household status — she does not arrive empty-handed or without attendants. The marriage integrates Nabal&#8217;s estate networks into David&#8217;s growing social base in Judah.</p>",

"43": "<p>The brief notice of Ahinoam of Jezreel as David&#8217;s other wife. Jezreel (upper Jezreel valley) represents a northern connection; Abigail (Carmel/Maon area) a southern Judean connection. David&#8217;s two wives at this point mirror his bicameral political situation — his network spans north-south Israelite territory even while he is in the wilderness. The enumeration &#8220;both of them were his wives&#8221; (<em>wattihyênāh gam šᵉtêhem lô lᵉnāšîm</em>) is a flat notational statement, not an endorsement or critique of polygamy, but a record of expanding political alliances through marriage.</p>",

"44": "<p>Saul&#8217;s unilateral dissolution of David&#8217;s marriage to Michal: he gives her to Palti (Paltiel) son of Laish of Gallim. The act is simultaneously a political move (denying David any dynastic claim through Saul&#8217;s daughter) and a violation of the marriage bond David had earned by the bride-price of Philistine foreskins (1 Sam 18:27). Michal&#8217;s fate — handed to another man — complicates David&#8217;s later retrieval of her (2 Sam 3:13-16). The closing note juxtaposes David&#8217;s two new marriages with Saul&#8217;s taking of his first; David gains two alliances; Saul cancels one.</p>"
},
"26": {
"1": "<p>The Ziphites again report David&#8217;s location to Saul at Gibeah — <em>hălōʾ dāwid mistattēr bᵉgibʿat haḥăḵîlāh</em>. This is the second Ziphite betrayal (cf. ch23:19); the repetition shows both David&#8217;s persistent vulnerability and the ongoing threat from within Judah. The Ziphites&#8217; willingness to betray a fellow Judahite suggests that Saul&#8217;s royal authority retained meaningful allegiance even in the south, complicating the picture of David as uniformly supported in his tribal territory.</p>",

"2": "<p>Saul&#8217;s force: three thousand <em>bᵉḥûrê yiśrāʾēl</em> (chosen/elite men of Israel) — the same number as David&#8217;s force before the desertion in ch13. The precision of &#8220;three thousand&#8221; signals a serious military expedition rather than a police pursuit; Saul deploys his royal guard against one man. The description <em>bᵉḵōl yisrāʾēl</em> (from all Israel) emphasizes the national scope of Saul&#8217;s hunt, which David will later cite (v19) as a reason YHWH should judge between them.</p>",

"3": "<p>Saul camps on the hill of Hachilah (<em>gibʿat haḥăḵîlāh</em>) alongside the road east of the Jeshimon (<em>ʿal pᵉnê hayyᵉšîmōn</em>). The Jeshimon is the desolate wasteland terrain of the eastern Judean wilderness — the barren, ravined landscape that provided both hiding and hardship. David, living in the wilderness, sees the camp when Saul arrives; his reconnaissance is immediate and shows superior tactical awareness.</p>",

"4": "<p>David sends spies (<em>mᵉragᵉlîm</em>) and confirms that Saul has truly come (<em>nāḵôn bāʾ šāʾûl</em>). The use of <em>nāḵôn</em> (confirmed, established) is the same root used for the &#8220;established&#8221; kingdom — there is an irony that the same vocabulary of certainty applies to both the promised Davidic dynasty and the confirmed threat against David&#8217;s life. Intelligence-gathering precedes David&#8217;s every major action; he acts from confirmed information, not rumor.</p>",

"5": "<p>David&#8217;s personal reconnaissance of Saul&#8217;s camp at night: he goes and sees where Saul lies, with Abner son of Ner (army commander) beside him, and the army encamped around them. The description of Saul sleeping in the camp (<em>šōkēḇ bammַaʿgāl</em> — sleeping in the wagon circle/encampment) with protective formation around him creates the scene David will penetrate. The precise intelligence — Abner&#8217;s position, the circular camp formation — shows David&#8217;s tactical acuity.</p>",

"6": "<p>David&#8217;s question: who will go down with me to Saul&#8217;s camp? He addresses Ahimelech the Hittite (otherwise unknown) and Abishai son of Zeruiah, Joab&#8217;s brother. The question is characteristically Davidic — consultation before action, even on a volunteer basis. Abishai&#8217;s willingness (<em>ʾănî ʾērēd ʿimmāḵ</em>) reflects the absolute loyalty of David&#8217;s inner circle; &#8220;I will go with you&#8221; without knowing the objective is the language of covenant commitment.</p>",

"7": "<p>David and Abishai penetrate the camp at night: Saul lies sleeping with his spear stuck in the ground at his head (<em>ḥănîtô ṭᵉʾûʾāh baʾāretz mᵉraʾăšōtāyw</em>), with Abner and the army sleeping around him. The spear at his head is the royal insignia — the same spear he hurled at David twice (1 Sam 18:11; 19:10) and at Jonathan (20:33). That it stands at his head while he sleeps vulnerable before David creates a precise irony of reversal — the weapon of attempted murder is now the marker of the sleeping pursuer&#8217;s helplessness.</p>",

"8": "<p>Abishai&#8217;s proposition: <em>sāgar ʾelōhîm ʾet ʾōyiḇᵉḵā bᵉyāḏᵉḵā hayyôm</em> — God has shut up your enemy into your hand today. The verb <em>sāgar</em> (to shut/enclose) is the vocabulary of divine military delivery (cf. Deut 23:15; Josh 20:5). Abishai&#8217;s theological interpretation is not wrong in principle — God does deliver enemies — but his application is wrong in this case. He proposes pinning Saul to the ground with his own spear in a single stroke: <em>wᵉʾiśmrennû bāḥănît wᵉʾel hāʾāreṣ ʿat pāʿam</em> — I will not need to strike him twice.</p>",

"10": "<p>David&#8217;s theological counter: <em>ḥay YHWH kî ʾim YHWH yiggāpennû</em> — as YHWH lives, YHWH himself will strike him down. David articulates three possible divine modes of Saul&#8217;s death: his day coming (<em>yôm môtô</em>), falling in battle (<em>baMMilḥāmāh wᵉnispāh</em>), or some other divine act. The comprehensive list — natural death, battle death, plague — covers all possibilities by which YHWH might judge Saul without David lifting a hand. The theological principle: YHWH judges kings; it is not David&#8217;s role to execute judgment on the LORD&#8217;s anointed.</p>",

"11": "<p><em>ḥālîlāh llî mēYHWH mishᵉlaḥ yāḏî bimšîaḥ YHWH</em> — far be it from me before YHWH that I should stretch out my hand against YHWH&#8217;s anointed. David&#8217;s restraint is explicitly grounded in the inviolability of the <em>māšîaḥ</em> status — not Saul&#8217;s person or power but his anointed office. The same principle that protects David (as YHWH&#8217;s future anointed) constrains him regarding Saul (as YHWH&#8217;s current anointed). Instead of the spear, David takes the spear and water jug — symbols of royal provision and military power — as evidence without executing judgment.</p>",

"13": "<p>David crosses to the other side (<em>wayyaʿăḇōr</em>) and stands on the top of the hill far away — a great space (<em>māqôm rāḥôq</em>) between them, distance that ensures safety for the confrontation to follow. The topographic detail — hilltop to hilltop, separated by valley — creates the stage for the shouted dialogue. The distance also signals David&#8217;s innocence: he did not use the opportunity for assassination but removed himself and then spoke. The space between them is the space of his restraint.</p>",

"14": "<p>David calls out to Abner: <em>hălōʾ taʿăneh ʾaḇnēr</em> — will you not answer? The rebuke is directed at the army commander responsible for guarding the king. David&#8217;s challenge from the far hilltop — &#8220;Are you a man?&#8221; — uses masculine honor vocabulary to shame Abner before his own troops. The question &#8220;who is like you in Israel?&#8221; (<em>mî kāmōḵā bᵉyisrāʾēl</em>) is ironic praise: Abner&#8217;s reputation makes his failure to guard the king all the more inexcusable.</p>",

"15": "<p>David&#8217;s evidence: <em>rᵉʾēh ʾet ḥănît hammelek wᵉʾet ṣappāḥat haMMayim ʾăšer mᵉraʾăšōtāyw</em> — see the king&#8217;s spear and the water jug that was at his head. The two items he has taken are the king&#8217;s most personal possessions — the royal weapon and the drinking vessel. Their possession proves David&#8217;s complete access to Saul&#8217;s person. The rebuke of Abner&#8217;s failure — &#8220;you have not guarded your lord the king&#8221; — names the dereliction explicitly; a royal guard who fails deserves death.</p>",

"16": "<p><em>ṭôḇ haddāḇār hazzeh ʾăšer ʿāśîtā ḥay YHWH kî ḇᵉnê māwet ʾattem</em> — this thing you have done is not good; as the LORD lives, you sons of death (deserve death). The judgment that Abner and the guard deserve death (<em>bᵉnê māwet</em> — sons/deserving of death) is ironic against the background of the entire pursuit narrative: those who pursue David to bring about his death have themselves deserved death by failing in their guard duty. The moral reversal is complete — David, the target, pronounces judgment on his pursuers.</p>",

"17": "<p>Saul recognizes David&#8217;s voice across the valley — <em>hăqôlᵉḵā zeh bᵉnî dāwîḏ</em> — is this your voice, David my son? The tender address &#8220;my son David&#8221; recurs in each of the David-Saul sparing episodes (cf. 24:17), creating a tragic refrain. Saul&#8217;s recognition of the voice that could have ended his life but did not is simultaneously relief and self-indictment — the man he tried to kill has spared him again.</p>",

"18": "<p>David&#8217;s legal brief: <em>lāmmāh zeh ʾăḏōnî rōḏēp ʾaḥărê ʿaḇdô</em> — why does my lord pursue his servant? The questions that follow — what have I done? what harm is in my hands? — are the standard formulas of an innocent party appealing for legal vindication (cf. Ps 7:3-5). David frames the pursuit as legally unjustified, inviting Saul to articulate the charge or abandon the prosecution.</p>",

"19": "<p>David&#8217;s theological argument about the meaning of exile: if YHWH has stirred Saul against David, let an offering appease him (<em>yāriaḥ minḥāh</em>). But if humans (<em>bᵉnê hāʾāḏām</em>) have incited him, they are cursed before YHWH — for they have driven David out (<em>gēraš</em>) from attaching himself to the inheritance of YHWH (<em>lᵉhisṯappēaḥ bᵉnaḥălat YHWH</em>), saying &#8220;Go, serve other gods.&#8221; This is David&#8217;s deepest theological complaint: exile from the land is exile from covenantal worship of YHWH, effectively a forced apostasy. The argument treats territorial displacement as a theological crisis, not merely a personal hardship.</p>",

"20": "<p><em>wᵉʿattāh ʾal yippōl dāmî ʾarṣāh minneged pᵉnê YHWH</em> — now do not let my blood fall to the ground away from the presence of YHWH. The phrase <em>minneged pᵉnê YHWH</em> (away from the presence of YHWH) identifies death in exile as the worst fate — dying outside the land is dying &#8220;far from YHWH&#8217;s face.&#8221; The image of the king of Israel hunting a single flea (<em>parʿōš</em>) or a partridge (<em>qōrēʾ</em>) in the mountains is deliberately bathetic — the mighty army pursuing a tiny bird captures the disproportionality of Saul&#8217;s vendetta.</p>",

"21": "<p>Saul&#8217;s third confession: <em>ḥāṭāʾtî šûḇ bᵉnî dāwid</em> — I have sinned; come back, my son David. The third use of the confession formula in the David-Saul narrative (cf. 15:24-30; 24:17) marks a pattern of recurring contrition without repentance. Each confession is followed by resumption of pursuit. <em>Lōʾ ʾāraʿ lᵉḵā ʿôḏ</em> — I will not do you harm again — is the promise that the narrative has already shown to be unreliable. Saul&#8217;s self-assessment — &#8220;I have played the fool (<em>sāḵaltî</em>) and erred greatly (<em>wāʾešgeh harbēh mᵉʾōḏ</em>)&#8221; — uses the vocabulary of wisdom failure alongside moral failure.</p>",

"22": "<p>David&#8217;s response holds both mercy and distance: here is the king&#8217;s spear (<em>hinnēh ḥănît hammelek</em>) — let one of the young men come over and get it. David returns the royal property but does not return himself. The return of the spear is an act of symbolic reconciliation — the weapon that Saul threw at David twice is returned as an act of mercy — but David refuses the personal proximity that would make Saul&#8217;s promise meaningful. Wisdom about unreliable repentance is not lack of forgiveness; David forgives without trusting.</p>",

"24": "<p><em>wᵉhinnēh kaʾăšer gāḏᵉlāh napšᵉḵā hayyôm hayyōm bᵉʿênāy kēn tigdal napšî bᵉʿênê YHWH</em> — as your life was precious in my eyes today, so may my life be precious in the eyes of YHWH. The mutual-value formula creates a covenant of reciprocity: as I valued you, may YHWH value me. The appeal to YHWH&#8217;s valuation of David&#8217;s life is a prayer grounded in precedent — David&#8217;s mercy to Saul becomes the basis of his appeal for YHWH&#8217;s mercy to him. This is the theology of the Psalms&#8217; lament tradition in narrative form.</p>",

"25": "<p>Saul&#8217;s final blessing of David in this episode: <em>bārûḵ ʾattāh bᵉnî dāwid gam ʿāśōh taʿăśeh wᵉgam yāḵōl tûḵāl</em> — blessed are you, my son David; you will indeed accomplish and you will indeed prevail. The cognate infinitives (<em>ʿāśōh taʿăśeh</em> — do doing; <em>yāḵōl tûḵāl</em> — prevail prevailing) express emphatic certainty. Saul&#8217;s blessing of the man he has been trying to kill is the ironic climax of the episode — the rejected king pronouncing the inevitable triumph of his replacement. David returns to his way; Saul to his place. The separation is final.</p>"
},
"27": {
"2": "<p>David crosses to Gath with his six hundred men (<em>wᵉhûʾ wᵉšeš mēʾôt ʾîš ʾimô</em>), going to Achish son of Maoch, king of Gath. The specific identification of the Gath king as Maoch&#8217;s son (distinguishing him from the Achish of ch21 who was apparently Maor&#8217;s son, or perhaps the same person with a different patronym) reflects the narrator&#8217;s precision. The decision to go to Gath with six hundred men is a military as well as political move — David brings a credible fighting force that Achish can use, creating mutual benefit.</p>",

"3": "<p>David settles (<em>wayyēšeḇ dāwid ʿim ʾāḵîš bᵉGat</em>) with Achish along with his men and their households — including his two wives Ahinoam and Abigail. The move of entire households signals permanence of resettlement, not merely temporary refuge. David has given up on survival in Israelite territory under Saul and is committing to a Philistine base. The inclusion of his wives marks this as full domestic transplantation, not just military alliance.</p>",

"4": "<p>Saul learns that David has fled to Gath and stops searching (<em>wayyᵉḥaḏal lᵉḇaqqēš ʾōtô</em>). The cessation of Saul&#8217;s pursuit achieves what David sought — safety from the immediate threat. Saul&#8217;s abandonment of the pursuit is rational: David with six hundred men among the Philistines is beyond practical reach. The irony is that David&#8217;s safety comes from throwing himself on the mercy of Israel&#8217;s primary enemy — a decision that will create its own moral and political complications (ch29).</p>",

"5": "<p>David&#8217;s request for a rural town: <em>nittᵉnāh lî māqôm bᵉʾaḥat ʿārê haśśāḏeh wᵉʾēšᵉḇāh šām</em> — give me a place in one of the towns of the field that I may settle there. The request to move out of the capital city (Gath) to a provincial town is politically shrewd: David reduces his visibility within Achish&#8217;s court while retaining the alliance. The rhetorical reason given — &#8220;why should your servant dwell in the royal city with you?&#8221; — is face-saving for Achish while serving David&#8217;s strategic purposes.</p>",

"7": "<p>David&#8217;s time in Philistine territory: <em>wᵉhāyāh mispar hayyāmîm ʾăšer yāšaḇ dāwid biśᵉḏēh pᵉlištîm yāmîm wᵉʾarbāʿāh ḥōḏāšîm</em> — the count of days David lived in Philistine fields was days and four months, i.e., one year and four months. The term <em>yāmîm</em> used here as &#8220;a year&#8221; (a Hebrew idiom for an indeterminate period typically meaning a year) plus four months gives the total stay. The precision is unusual in narrative — the narrator marks the duration as significant for the chronology of David&#8217;s pre-kingship period.</p>",

"8": "<p>David&#8217;s raiding policy: he raids the Geshurites, the Girzites, and the Amalekites — peoples who were <em>yōšᵉḇê hāʾāreṣ mēʿôlām</em> (inhabitants of the land from of old). The Geshurites (not the Geshurites of Aram-Geshur) and Girzites are archaic pre-Israelite populations in the Negev approaches; the Amalekites are Israel&#8217;s longstanding enemies (cf. 1 Sam 15). David targets populations that are both politically safe to attack (no Philistine allegiance) and theologically legitimate (traditional enemies of Israel), maintaining covenantal consistency even while serving a Philistine overlord.</p>",

"9": "<p>David&#8217;s total-destruction policy: <em>wᵉhikkāh dāwid ʾet hāʾāreṣ wᵉlōʾ yᵉḥayyeh ʾîš wᵉʾiššāh</em> — David would strike the land and leave alive neither man nor woman. The no-survivors policy is both military — preventing intelligence reports — and consistent with the <em>ḥerem</em> (total destruction) principle applied to Amalekites. The spoil — sheep, oxen, donkeys, camels, clothing — is brought back to Achish. David&#8217;s application of <em>ḥerem</em> against Amalekites is ironic given Saul&#8217;s failure to do so (ch15), but his motivation here is strategic deception rather than covenantal obedience.</p>",

"10": "<p>Achish&#8217;s question: <em>ʾal pᵉšaṭtem hayyôm</em> — where have you raided today? David&#8217;s deceptive answer claims raids against the Negeb of Judah, the Negeb of the Jerahmeelites, and the Negeb of the Kenites — Israelite-adjacent territories. The deception is strategic: Achish believes David is attacking his own people, making him persona non grata in Israel and permanently dependent on Philistine patronage. David&#8217;s multilevel deception — raiding Israel&#8217;s enemies while claiming to raid Israel&#8217;s allies — is narratively presented as clever survival, not moral exemplar.</p>",

"11": "<p>The no-survivors policy serves intelligence security: <em>wᵉdāwid lōʾ yᵉḥayyeh ʾîš wᵉʾiššāh lᵉhāḇîʾ Gat lēʾmōr pen yagîḏû ʿālênû lēʾmōr kōh ʿāśāh dāwid</em> — David left no man or woman alive to bring back to Gath, saying they would tell what David had really done. The narrator explicitly provides David&#8217;s reasoning, making the deception transparent to the reader even while Achish remains deceived. The phrase <em>wᵉḵēn miš pāṭô kol hayyāmîm ʾăšer yāšaḇ biśᵉḏēh pᵉlištîm</em> — and this was his practice all the days he lived in Philistine territory — shows the systematic nature of the deception over sixteen months.</p>",

"12": "<p>Achish&#8217;s complete trust in David: <em>wayyaʾămēn ʾāḵîš bᵉdāwid lēʾmōr haḇʾēš hibʾîš bᵉʿammô bᵉyiśrāʾēl</em> — Achish trusted David, thinking David had made himself utterly repulsive to his own people in Israel. The verb <em>baʾš</em> (to stink, to make oneself odious) is used of social excommunication — the same root used when Israel &#8220;became odious&#8221; to the Philistines in ch13:4. Achish believes David has permanently burned his bridges with Israel, becoming a &#8220;servant forever&#8221; (<em>lî lᵉʿeḇed ʿôlām</em>). The irony is complete: the Philistine king trusts the man who has been systematically deceiving him, while believing the man whose loyalty is entirely to YHWH and Israel.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    out_path = "data/commentary/mkt-original/1samuel.json"
    existing = load_comm(out_path)
    before = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    after = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    save_comm(out_path, existing)
    print(f"  wrote {out_path}")
    print(f"1samuel mkt-original: added up to {after - before} verses across ch25-27")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
